label("$15$",(B+A)/2,S);
label("$17$",(B+C)/2,NE);
label("$h$",(O+C)/2,W);
label("$\frac{15\cdot 8}{17}$",(B+O)/2,N);
[/asy]

The area of the triangle is $\frac{1}{2}(8)(15) = 60,$ so the length of the altitude to the hypotenuse is $$h=\frac{2\cdot60}{17} = \frac{120}{17}.$$The length of the altitude to the base of the right triangle is $\frac{15\cdot 8}{17}.$ Therefore, the sum of the lengths of the two longest altitudes is $$\frac{120}{17}+\frac{15\cdot 8}{17}=\frac{240}{17}=\boxed{\frac{240}{17}}.$$

